implements EditableSModel
    Editable model (generally) backed up by file. Implicitly bound to files due to rename and changeModelFile methods, for a generic editable model, see EditableModelDescriptor evgeny, 11/21/12

      • save

        public final void save()
        Description copied from interface: EditableSModel
        needs the write action lock, this method will save the model into the storage (located at SModel.getSource()). If EditableSModel.needsReloading() is false then as a result of this method EditableSModel.isChanged() returns true Otherwise the actual save can happen much later.
        Specified by:
        save in interface EditableSModel
        See Also:
        EditableSModel.save(SaveOptions)

      • save

        public CompletionStage<SaveResult> save​(@NotNull
                                        SaveOptions options)
        Specified by:
        save in interface EditableSModel
        Parameters:
        options - describe how to behave in case of conflict where 'conflict' is the scenario when we save a changed model ({EditableSModel.isChanged()} is true) and it happens that {EditableSModel.needsReloading()} is true.
        Returns:
        a CompletionStage with the result inside. yes, the save might not happen right away after the invocation, for example if there is a conflict with data source ({EditableSModel.needsReloading() returned true} and the implementor might overwrite the data coming from the data source which is not good (losing data is never good). Realistically in 2020.3 this is the only case when the result is async, but still. Perhaps, the api could be more solid with all the {EditableSModel.needsReloading()} logic happening outside of EditableSModel implementations (@see EditableSModelBase#areThereAnyConflictsOnSave). But as always I doubt that changing the semantics of such a popular method is the right way
